83// Represents a stream of dependent computations on a GPU device.
84//
85// The operations within a stream execute linearly and asynchronously until
86// BlockHostUntilDone() is invoked, which synchronously joins host code with
87// the execution of the stream.
88//
89// If any given operation fails when entraining work for the stream, ok() will
90// indicate that an error has occurred. After initialization, once a stream is
91// !ok(), it will never be ok().
92//
93// Thread-safe post-initialization.
94class Stream {
95 public:
96 // Instantiate a stream tied to parent as a platform executor. Work
97 // entrained onto this stream will be launched/managed on that
98 // StreamExecutor's platform.
99 explicit Stream(StreamExecutor *parent);
100
101 // Test only. Use an externally-populated value (like a mock) for the
102 // platform-specific stream implementation.
103 Stream(StreamExecutor *parent, internal::StreamInterface *implementation);
104
105 // Deallocates any stream resources that the parent StreamExecutor has
106 // bestowed
107 // upon this object.
108 ~Stream();
109
110 // Returns whether any errors have occurred while entraining work for this
111 // stream.
112 bool ok() const { return !InErrorState(); }
113
114 // Initialize the stream. This must be performed before entraining any other
115 // operations.
116 Stream &Init() LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_);
117
118 // Initializes timer t via the StreamExecutor.
119 Stream &InitTimer(Timer *t);
120
121 // Convenience wrapper around Init() and InitTimer().
122 Stream &InitWithTimer(Timer *t);
123
124 // Get or create a sub-stream from this stream. If there is any sub-stream in
125 // the pool that can be reused then just return this sub-stream. Otherwise
126 // create a new sub-stream.
127 Stream *GetOrCreateSubStream() LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_);
128
129 // Return the sub-stream back to the host stream so that it can be reused
130 // later.
131 void ReturnSubStream(Stream *sub_stream) LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_);
132
133 // Allocate temporary memories. The stream will deallocate them when blocked
134 // or destroyed.
135 template <typename T>
136 port::StatusOr<std::unique_ptr<TemporaryDeviceMemory<T>>>
137 AllocateTemporaryArray(uint64 element_count);
138
139 // Entrains onto the stream of operations: a kernel launch with the given
140 // (variadic) parameters for the invocation. These arguments can be things
141 // like DeviceMemory or primitive types such as int. What arguments you may
142 // pass to a given kernel are noted as the template parameters to the
143 // TypedKernel type that the machocc compiler generates.
144 //
145 // Template parameters:
146 // Params... The type list of formal parameters that the typed kernel
147 // expects, which is matched against Args...
148 // Args... The deduced type list for passed actual arguments
149 //
150 // Implementation: A compile-time compatibility check is performed that has
151 // some leniency versus an exact parameter pack match -- for example,
152 // `const DeviceMemory<T>` is considered "pack compatible" with a
153 // `const DeviceMemory<T>&` formal parameter; in part, because we don't have
154 // perfect forwarding support without rvalue references. It also attempts to
155 // spit out helpful static_assert error traces with information as to the
156 // argument number and types that were mismatched.
157 template <typename... Params, typename... Args>
158 Stream &ThenLaunch(ThreadDim thread_dims, BlockDim block_dims,
159 const TypedKernel<Params...> &kernel, Args... args);
160
161 // Record a "start" event for the interval timer at this point in the
162 // stream's
163 // execution (relative to the previously and subsequently enqueued items in
164 // the stream's execution). Streams may be started/stopped multiple times.
165 Stream &ThenStartTimer(Timer *t);
166
167 // Record a "stop" event for the interval timer at this point in the
168 // stream's
169 // execution. See also Stream::ThenStartTimer.
170 Stream &ThenStopTimer(Timer *t);
171
172 // TODO(leary) If work is added to the stream that is being depended upon,
173 // then what? Have to describe what happens.
174 template <typename... Params>
175 Stream &ThenWaitFor(Stream *other, Params... more_streams) {
176 return ThenWaitFor(more_streams...).ThenWaitFor(other);
177 }
178
179 // Create a dependency for this stream's next work on the other stream
180 // completing. Does not take ownership of other, and other must not be
181 // null.
182 //
183 // Checks that a stream does not wait for itself, and it is up to the
184 // user to guarantee that a stream does not come to wait on itself in a
185 // cyclic
186 // manner; in that case, behavior is undefined.
187 //
188 // N.B. Base recursion case for the variadic ThenWaitFor.
189 Stream &ThenWaitFor(Stream *other);
190
191 // Waits for all streams values in others.
192 // Checks that there is no shallow circular wait (i.e. that "this" is not in
193 // others)
194 template <typename P>
195 Stream &ThenWaitFor(P others) {
196 for (auto &stream : *others) {
197 CHECK_NE(stream.get(), this);
198 ThenWaitFor(stream.get());
199 }
200 return *this;
201 }
202
203 // Waits for an event object to be set.
204 // Note that ThenRecordEvent must have been called on the event before
205 // you call this function; otherwise the event will be considered complete
206 // and this wait will do nothing.
207 Stream &ThenWaitFor(Event *event);
208
209 // Inserts the specified event into the end of this stream. Once the stream
210 // has processed all events prior to the insertion point, the event will be
211 // marked as completed.
212 // The stream does not take ownership of event - meaning that event's lifetime
213 // must extend past the point at which it is marked complete!
214 Stream &ThenRecordEvent(Event *event);

718 // dimensions) and growing another dimension (or set of dimensions), while

726 // Depth to space takes an X by Y image with depth D*M and changes it to an
727 // MX x MY image with depth D. Each input location (x,y) with depth D*M in
728 // the input image is changed to an MxM contiguous area in the output image,
729 // with the values being laid out in raster order specified by
730 // DepthToSpaceLayout, and will have a new depth of D.
731 // See the DoDepthToSpace comment for more information.
732 Stream &ThenDepthToSpace(const dnn::BatchDescriptor &input_dimensions,
733 const DeviceMemory<float> &input_data,
734 const dnn::DepthToSpaceLayout &depth_to_space_layout,
735 const int sqrt_depth_reduction,
736 DeviceMemory<float> *output_data);
737
738 // Space to depth is the inverse of depth to space. Space to depth takes each
739 // non-overlapping M by M patch (in the X and Y dimensions) with depth D of
740 // the input, and transforms it to a 1 by 1 patch with depth D*M. If the
741 // input has size (MX, MY, D), the output has size (X, Y, D*M). The number of
742 // data elements is not changed.
743 Stream &ThenSpaceToDepth(const dnn::BatchDescriptor &input_dimensions,
744 const DeviceMemory<float> &input_data,
745 const dnn::DepthToSpaceLayout &space_to_depth_layout,
746 const int sqrt_depth_increase,
747 DeviceMemory<float> *output_data);

1695 // Makes the RNG use the provided value as the basis for further generation.
1696 // /dev/urandom (good) and /dev/random (better, but sometimes slow) are good
1697 // sources of seed data if the default (high quality) sources are not
1698 // desired.
1699 // For most use cases, this function will not be necessary; each provided
1700 // back-end implementation will be appropriately seeded by default.
1701 // At a minimum 16 bytes of data are required in the seed buffer.
1702 //
1703 // To seed with good (non-reproducible) data:
1704 // File* f = File::Open("/dev/random", "r");
1705 // int64 bytes_read = f->Read(seed_data, bytes_to_read);
1706 // < error checking >
1707 // stream.ThenSetRngSeed(seed_data, bytes_read);
1708 //
1709 // To seed with reproducible data:
1710 // uint64_t seed_data[2] = { <data> };
1711 // stream.ThenSetRngSeed(seed_data, 16);
1712 Stream &ThenSetRngSeed(const uint8 *seed, uint64 seed_bytes);

1742 // Alternative interface for memcpying from device to host that takes an
1743 // array slice. Checks that the destination size can accommodate the host
1744 // slice size.
1745 template <typename T>
1746 Stream &ThenMemcpyD2H(const DeviceMemory<T> &gpu_src,
1747 port::MutableArraySlice<T> host_dst) {
1748 auto host_size = host_dst.size() * sizeof(T);
1749 CHECK(gpu_src.size() == 0 || host_size >= gpu_src.size());
1750 return ThenMemcpy(host_dst.begin(), gpu_src, host_size);
1751 }
1752
1753 // Alternative interface for memcpying from host to device that takes an
1754 // array slice. Checks that the destination size can accommodate the host
1755 // slice size.
1756 template <typename T>
1757 Stream &ThenMemcpyH2D(port::ArraySlice<T> host_src,
1758 DeviceMemory<T> *gpu_dst) {
1759 auto host_size = host_src.size() * sizeof(T);
1760 CHECK(gpu_dst->size() == 0 || gpu_dst->size() >= host_size);
1761 return ThenMemcpy(gpu_dst, host_src.begin(), host_size);
1762 }

1770 // Calls to the device-to-device copy overload of ThenMemcpy -- useful for

1772 // device pointer if you're not doing metaprogramming against the API.
1773 Stream &ThenMemcpyD2D(DeviceMemoryBase *gpu_dst,
1774 const DeviceMemoryBase &gpu_src, uint64 size) {

1943 // (Synchronously) block the host code waiting for the operations
1944 // entrained on the stream (enqueued to this point in program
1945 // execution) to complete.
1946 //
1947 // Returns an OK status if the blocking was successful and the stream is ok().
1948 // Otherwise returns an error describing why the blocking failed.
1949 port::Status BlockHostUntilDone() LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_);
1950
1951 // Warning! This method interacts with internal threads in
1952 // sometimes-unpredictable ways and is intended for GPU-Executor-internal
1953 // use
1954 // only. Please check with a member of the FASTR team before making use of
1955 // this method.
1956 //
1957 // Entrains onto the stream a function to be executed on the host at some
1958 // point in the future.
1959 // Async host callbacks DO NOT block the stream as device functions (or as
1960 // synchronous host callbacks). No synchronization is possible with
1961 // asynchronous callbacks; they are strictly fire-and-forget.
1962 // This method is private due to the potential for undefined behavior with
1963 // synchronization using OpenCL user events.
1964 // The ONLY lifetime guarantee in these calls is that the StreamExecutor
1965 // parameter will still be valid - this Stream may not be!
1966 // Any callbacks requiring device API calls must use this method.
1967 Stream &ThenEnqueueOnBackgroundThread(
1968 std::function<void(StreamExecutor *)> task);
1969
1970 // Returns the (opaque) platform-specific backing object. Ownership is not
1971 // transferred to the caller.
1972 internal::StreamInterface *implementation() { return implementation_.get(); }
1973
1974 // Entrains onto the stream a callback to the host (from the device).
1975 // Host callbacks block/occupy the stream just as device functions
1976 // (execute one at a time, block later stream operations).
1977 //
1978 // Behavior is undefined when synchronizing using OpenCL user events.
1979 // Behavior is undefined if host callbacks call device routines or insert
1980 // them into any stream.
1981 //
1982 // On certain platforms, ThenDoHostCallback is expected to have significant
1983 // negative effects on performance.
1984 Stream &ThenDoHostCallback(std::function<void()> callback);

1988 CHECK(parent_ != nullptr);
1989 return parent_;
1990 }

2004 bool InErrorState() const LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_) {
2005 tf_shared_lock lock{mu_};
2006 return !ok_;
2007 }
2008
2009 // Sets the error state if operation_retcode is false.
2010 // This is a useful shorthand for many stream routines.
2011 void CheckError(bool operation_retcode) LOCKS_EXCLUDED(mu_) {
2012 if (operation_retcode) {
2013 return;
2014 }
2015 mutex_lock lock{mu_};
2016 ok_ = false;
2017 }
2018
2019 void SetError() { CheckError(false /* = operation_retcode */); }
2020
2021 void SetErrorAndLogNoDnnSupport() {
2022 SetError();
2023 LOG(WARNING) << "attempting to perform DNN operation using StreamExecutor "
2024 "without DNN support";
2025 }
2026
2027 // The StreamExecutor that supports the operation of this stream.
2028 StreamExecutor *parent_;
2029
2030 // The platform-dependent implementation that the StreamExecutor interface
2031 // delegates to.
2032 std::unique_ptr<internal::StreamInterface> implementation_;
2033
2034 // mutex that guards the allocation / error state flags.
2035 // Mutable so that it can be obtained via const reader lock.
2036 mutable mutex mu_;
2037
2038 // Whether Init() was successfully called to allocate this stream on the
2039 // underlying platform. It simply flips from 0 to 1 with a sanity check.
2040 // See StreamExecutor::AllocateStream.
2041 bool allocated_ GUARDED_BY(mu_);
2042
2043 // Whether all operations have entrained successfully to the current program
2044 // point.
2045 bool ok_ GUARDED_BY(mu_);
2046
2047 // Sub-streams that are generated from this stream. Each element has a pointer
2048 // to sub-stream and a boolean value indicating if this substream is ready to
2049 // be reused.
2050 std::vector<std::pair<std::unique_ptr<Stream>, bool>> sub_streams_
2051 GUARDED_BY(mu_);
2052
2053 // Streams can allocate temporary memories to help with work they enqueue
2054 // (e.g. for scratch memory spaces). This member tracks those allocations and
2055 // notes when they can be reclaimed -- reclamation is attempted when
2056 // BlockHostUntilDone() is called.
2057 internal::TemporaryMemoryManager temporary_memory_manager_;
2058
2059 // Implementation of ThenConvolveBackwardBias that is shared by all types.
2060 template <typename T>
2061 Stream &ThenConvolveBackwardBiasImpl(
2062 const dnn::BatchDescriptor &input_descriptor,
2063 const DeviceMemory<T> &input_data,
2064 const dnn::BatchDescriptor &bias_descriptor,
2065 DeviceMemory<T> *backward_bias_data);
2066
2067 SE_DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Stream);
2068};

2075Stream::AllocateTemporaryArray(uint64 element_count) {
2076 return temporary_memory_manager_.AllocateArray<T>(element_count);
2077}
